 \begin{abstract}
-The Galactic 511 keV annihilation line is a direct tracer of low-energy positrons, but its compact-source content and narrow-line kinematics remain difficult to measure because MeV observations are strongly background dominated. We evaluate a balloon-borne pointed 511 keV telescope that combines a Ge(111) Laue lens with a transition-edge-sensor (TES) microcalorimeter focal plane. The detector-coupled Monte Carlo model transports the focused optical signal, prompt atmospheric backgrounds, and delayed activation through the same engineering detector/cryostat mass model. The same event processing then applies the active-shield veto, Compton/field-of-view consistency selection, narrow line window, and mission-time rate fold. The baseline optical configuration has a 10 m focal length, $\aeff(511\keV)=20.08\,\mathrm{cm^2}$, and a $510.58$--$511.42\keV$ analysis window; delayed activity is emitted from sampled production positions recorded during activation transport. In the current fix5 full-statistics closure, a reference point-source flux of $10^{-4}\,\mathrm{ph\,cm^{-2}\,s^{-1}}$ gives day-15 selected line-window background and signal rates of $3.92\times10^{-2}\cps$ and $1.19\times10^{-3}\cps$, respectively. Folding these selected rates over the mission-time profile gives $Z_{20\mathrm{d}}=7.80$, a $3\sigma$ detection time of 2.51 d, and a 20-d $3\sigma$ flux threshold of $3.85\times10^{-5}\cms$. The fixed day-15 delayed inventory is $85.449\,\mathrm{Bq}$ after the NUBASE ground-state correction, and the selected W/collimator-origin delayed audit finds zero W/collimator-origin selected events. Relative to the previous v3p5 exact-position authority, the current closure reduces the selected hard-window background to 0.623 of the reference value while preserving the focused signal response at 1.004. Secondary spatial-analysis and atmospheric-line-of-sight checks remain diagnostics; the hard-window fix5 calculation is the primary rate result. These results define a detector-coupled selected-rate basis for evaluating focused TES spectroscopy in narrow-line point-source searches, provided activation and prompt atmospheric backgrounds are modeled in the same selection space as the signal.
+The Galactic 511 keV line is the characteristic signature of electron--positron annihilation, but pointed measurements from balloon altitude are limited by atmospheric gamma rays, particle-induced instrumental background, and delayed radioactivation. We present a detector-coupled Monte Carlo estimate for a balloon-borne telescope combining a 10 m Ge(111) Laue lens with a transition-edge-sensor (TES) microcalorimeter focal plane. Focused source photons, prompt atmospheric particles and photons, and delayed radioactive decays are transported through a common detector/cryostat proxy mass model and subjected to the same event definition, including a CsI anticoincidence selection, a topology/field-of-view consistency test, and a $510.58$--$511.42\keV$ line window. Delayed decays are sampled from radionuclide-production coordinates recorded during activation transport. For a monochromatic point source with reference flux $10^{-4}\phcms$, the selected day-15 background and signal rates are $3.92\times10^{-2}\cps$ and $1.19\times10^{-3}\cps$, respectively; prompt atmospheric events account for about 93\% of the selected background. Under the adopted synthetic 20 d trajectory and continuous on-source exposure, the statistical counting metric gives $Z_{20\mathrm{d}}=7.80$, a net $3\sigma$ on-source exposure of 2.51 d, and a 20 d $3\sigma$ flux threshold of $3.85\times10^{-5}\phcms$. These values are statistical sensitivities for an unresolved line and the present reference mass model; they do not yet include a full-payload prompt-background model, diffuse-sky foregrounds, or systematic uncertainties in the atmospheric field, detector response, activation calculation, and background estimation.
 \end{abstract}
 
